        "content": "<p>Is it fair to say that a topological space is an arrow from a lattice <em>(with some additional limits)</em> to the image of the contravariant power set functor? Then, the category of topological spaces and continuous functions is the category of arrows to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">P</span></span></span></span> and commuting squares in the ambient category of lattices <em>(with some additional limits)</em>, like so:</p>\n<p><span class=\"katex-display\"><span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" display=\"block\"><semantics><mtable rowspacing=\"0.16em\" columnalign=\"center center center\" columnspacing=\"1em\"><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel=\"0\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mrow></mrow></mstyle></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel=\"0\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mi>L</mi></mstyle></mtd><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel=\"0\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\"><mover><mo><mo>⟵</mo></mo><mi>m</mi></mover></mo></mstyle></mtd><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel=\"0\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mi>K</mi></mstyle></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel=\"0\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mrow><mi>s</mi><mo fence=\"false\" stretchy=\"true\" minsize=\"1.8em\" maxsize=\"1.8em\">↓</mo><mphantom><mi>s</mi></mphantom></mrow></mstyle></mtd><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel=\"0\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\"><mover><mo><mo>⟶</mo></mo><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">⟨</mo><mi>f</mi><mo separator=\"true\">;</mo><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">⟩</mo></mrow></mover></mo></mstyle></mtd><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel=\"0\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mrow><mphantom><mi>t</mi></mphantom><mo fence=\"false\" stretchy=\"true\" minsize=\"1.8em\" maxsize=\"1.8em\">↓</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mstyle></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel=\"0\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>A</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mstyle></mtd><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel=\"0\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\"><mover><mo><mo>⟵</mo></mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">P</mi><mi>f</mi></mrow></mover></mo></mstyle></mtd><mtd><mstyle scriptlevel=\"0\" displaystyle=\"false\"><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"script\">P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>B</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow></mstyle></mtd></mtr></mtable><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\begin {array} {ccc}\n\\\\ L &amp; \\overset m \\longleftarrow &amp; K\n\\\\ s \\Big \\downarrow {\\phantom s} &amp; \\overset {⟨f; m⟩} \\longrightarrow &amp; {\\phantom t} \\Big \\downarrow t\n\\\\ \\mathcal P (A) &amp; \\overset {\\mathcal P f} \\longleftarrow &amp; \\mathcal P (B)\n\\end {array}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:6.4486em;vertical-align:-2.9743em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mtable\"><span class=\"arraycolsep\" style=\"width:0.5em;\"></span><span class=\"col-align-c\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:3.4743em;\"><span style=\"top:-6.0563em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3.422em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"></span></span><span style=\"top:-4.5839em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3.422em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">L</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-2.8019em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3.422em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"delimsizing mult\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.151em;\"><span style=\"top:-1.966em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.616em;\"></span><span class=\"delimsizinginner delim-size1\"><span>↓</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-2.558em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.616em;\"></span><span style=\"height:0.616em;width:0.6667em;\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width=\"0.6667em\" height=\"0.616em\" style=\"width:0.6667em\" viewBox=\"0 0 666.67 616\" preserveAspectRatio=\"xMinYMin\"><path d=\"M312 0 H355 V616 H312z M312 0 H355 V616 H312z\"/></svg></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.166em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.616em;\"></span><span class=\"delimsizinginner delim-size1\"><span>⏐</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.65em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"color:transparent;\">s</span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-0.8077em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3.422em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:2.9743em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"arraycolsep\" style=\"width:0.5em;\"></span><span class=\"arraycolsep\" style=\"width:0.5em;\"></span><span class=\"col-align-c\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:2.2743em;\"><span style=\"top:-4.5839em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3.422em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\"><span class=\"mop op-limits\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.1124em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span><span class=\"mop\">⟵</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.711em;margin-left:0em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">m</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.011em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-2.8019em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3.422em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\"><span class=\"mop op-limits\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.422em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span><span class=\"mop\">⟶</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.797em;margin-left:0em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mopen mtight\">⟨</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mpunct mtight\">;</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">m</span><span class=\"mclose mtight\">⟩</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.011em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-0.8077em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3.422em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\"><span class=\"mop op-limits\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.3442em;\"><span style=\"top:-3em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span><span class=\"mop\">⟵</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.7581em;margin-left:0em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathcal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">P</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.011em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:2.9743em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"arraycolsep\" style=\"width:0.5em;\"></span><span class=\"arraycolsep\" style=\"width:0.5em;\"></span><span class=\"col-align-c\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:2.2743em;\"><span style=\"top:-4.5839em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3.422em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">K</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-2.8019em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3.422em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"color:transparent;\">t</span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"delimsizing mult\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:1.151em;\"><span style=\"top:-1.966em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.616em;\"></span><span class=\"delimsizinginner delim-size1\"><span>↓</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-2.558em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.616em;\"></span><span style=\"height:0.616em;width:0.6667em;\"><svg xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/2000/svg\" width=\"0.6667em\" height=\"0.616em\" style=\"width:0.6667em\" viewBox=\"0 0 666.67 616\" preserveAspectRatio=\"xMinYMin\"><path d=\"M312 0 H355 V616 H312z M312 0 H355 V616 H312z\"/></svg></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.166em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.616em;\"></span><span class=\"delimsizinginner delim-size1\"><span>⏐</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.65em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span><span style=\"top:-0.8077em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:3.422em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:2.9743em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"arraycolsep\" style=\"width:0.5em;\"></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></p>\n<p>Here, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>s</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">s</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">t</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6151em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span> are two topological spaces and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">⟨</mo><mi>f</mi><mo separator=\"true\">;</mo><mi>m</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">⟩</mo><mo>:</mo><mi>s</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">⟨f; m⟩: s \\rightarrow t</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">⟨</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mpunct\">;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">m</span><span class=\"mclose\">⟩</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6151em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">t</span></span></span></span> is a continuous function.</p>\n<p>If this is true, I should expect this definition to appear in the first chapter of any introduction to topology, but I do not think I have ever seen it out there. Is my definition wrong?</p>",
        "id": 528195002,
        "sender_full_name": "Ignat Insarov",
        "timestamp": 1752208565
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don’t quite understand but I’m not sure if it’s just a superficial consequence of your word choices. What is the lattice, here? The lattice of opens of the space? And you want a function from this lattice to some powerset? Are you saying you want the topology to be a function <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T\\to P(X)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> rather than a subset of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P(X)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>? You could try that, but then “the same” open set can have multiple “names” in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">.</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">T.</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">T</span><span class=\"mord\">.</span></span></span></span> This is a reasonable sounding thing to do, for a category theorist, but would be hard to explain on the first page of a topology text. But maybe I’ve totally misread you?</p>",
        "id": 528197629,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
        "timestamp": 1752210567
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In \"point-free\" topology they throw away sets of points and instead focus on the lattice formed by the open subsets, but the resulting subject isn't quite the same as point-set topology.  Maybe you are noticing that much but not all information about a topological space is related to the algebraic properties of the lattice those spaces form?</p>",
        "id": 528198214,
        "sender_full_name": "Ryan Wisnesky",
        "timestamp": 1752210980
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In Chapter 5 of Vickers's \"Topology Via Logic\" he defines a <strong>topological system</strong> to be a relation <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>⊨</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\vDash</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6922em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel amsrm\">⊨</span></span></span></span> between a set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> (thought of as points) and a frame <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> (thought of as opens). Iirc he explicitly says these are the same thing as frame maps <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A \\to \\mathcal{P}(X)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, and compares this with the classical notion of a topology on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>. As Kevin said, they can't be exactly the same, because a frame map might not be injective, so that multiple elements of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> give the same set of points of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 528199890,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Grossack (she/they)",
        "timestamp": 1752212239
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What if we say <em>«a topological space is an equivalence class of monic arrows»</em> instead of simply <em>«an arrow»</em>? <del>Since lattices <em>(even with some additional limits)</em> are algebraic theories, monic arrows should simply be defined by one to one functions <em>(that respect the algebraic structure)</em>.</del> This makes the definition of a topological space very similar to the definition of a subset, which is an equivalence class of monic arrows in the category of sets and functions.</p>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"609515\">@Kevin Carlson</span> Yes, this is what I had in mind.<br>\n<span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"278546\">@Chris Grossack (she/they)</span> A book I did not know I need!</p>\n<p><strong>P. S.</strong> It turns out that even in concrete categories there can exist monic arrows other than one to one functions. This needs to be looked into, but I am out of time.</p>",
        "id": 528271753,
        "sender_full_name": "Ignat Insarov",
        "timestamp": 1752219420
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>An equivalence class of monic arrows is indeed nothing more than a subset (in this case: you haven’t set us in any category other than the category of sets), and “a subset of some <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>X</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P(X)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>” (closed under the usual conditions) is just the usual definition of topology.</p>",
        "id": 528371530,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Carlson",
        "timestamp": 1752250643
    }
]